Question: Is there a global principle governing the variants?

The Einstein Notation

  • Consider \(\sum_i c_i x^i = c_1 x^1 + c_2 x^2 + c_3 x^3\).

  • The summation is simplified as \(c_i x_i\). The paired subscript and superscript induce summation.

  • It applies to multiple summation: \(x_i^j y_j^k z_k^i = \sum_i \sum_j \sum_k x_i^j y_j^k z_k^i\).

Vector, Matrix, Tensor

  • Vector is regarded as a tensor with single superscript \(v^i\).

  • Matrix is regarded as a tensor with one subscript and one superscript \(M_j^i\).

  • The matrix product can be denoted in Einstein notation: \(y^j = M_i^j x^j\).

Superscript vs. Subscript

Superscripted → vector

\[\left [ v^i \right ] = \begin{bmatrix} v^0 \\ \vdots \\ v^N \end{bmatrix}\]

Subscripted → covector (or linear form)

\[\left [ v_i \right ] = \begin{bmatrix} v_0 && \cdots && v_N \end{bmatrix}\]

Raising or lowing the index can be understood as matrix transpose.

Tensor Contraction

  • For \(y^j = M_i^j x^j\), the values are summed up over index \(j\). We say index \(j\) is contracted.

  • Tensor is an algebraic object with multiple indexes \(T_{p_1, \cdots, p_N}^{q_1, \cdots, q_M}\)

  • The transformation of image from \(M\) to \(N\) pixels, and from \(C\) to \(D\) channels is denoted as \(Y^{n d} = T_{m c}^{n d} X^{m c}\).

Tensor Contraction

\[\begin{bmatrix} Y_{0,0} \\ \vdots \\ Y_{N,D} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} T_{0,0}^{0,0} && \cdots && T_{M,C}^{0,0} \\ \vdots && \ddots && \vdots \\ T_{0,0}^{N,D} && \cdots && T_{M,C}^{N,D} \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} X_{0,0} \\ \vdots \\ X_{M,C} \end{bmatrix}\]

Convolution Realized

Convolution in Tensor Algebra

Convolution is a restriction to the transformation in \(Y^{n d} = T_{m c}^{n d} X^{m c}\) such that

\[T_{m c}^{n d} = C_{k m}^{n} K_{c}^{k d}\]

The \(K\) is the convolution kernel indexed by input channel \(c\) and output channel \(d\).

Depth-wise Separable Convolution

Depth-wise separable convolution comprises of two steps.

  1. Depth-wise convolution: Independent convolution per channel (figure)

  2. Point-wise convolution: 1x1 convolution (figure)

Source: MobileNets: Efficient Convolutional Neural Networks for Mobile Vision Applications

Depth-wise Separable Convolution

Depth-wise separable convolution is a special case of convolution that can be decomposed.

\[T_{m c}^{n d} = C_{k m}^{n} K_{ c}^{k d} = C_{k m}^{n} P_{c}^{d} I^{c'} D_{c'}^{k}\]

where

  • \( D_{c'}^{k}\) is depth-wise convolution kernel, \(I^{c'}\) is constant 1 tensor.

  • \(P_{c}^{d}\) forms a point-wise convolution kernel.

Depth-wise Separable Convolution

  • Convolution kernel \(K_c^{k d}\) has \(k c d\) parameters.

  • Depth-wise separable convolution kernels \(D_{c'}^k, P_{c}^{d}\) have \(k c + c d\) parameters.

Grouped Convolution

We divide both input \(c\) and output \(d\) channels into \(v\) groups. Each group independently runs convolution.

Grouped Convolution Kernel

  • There are \(v\) groups.

  • Each group has \(\frac{c}{v}\) input channels and \(\frac{d}{v}\) output channels.

  • Each group has a convolution kernel with \(k \cdot \frac{c}{v} \cdot \frac{d}{v}\) parameters. Thus, \(\frac{k c d}{v}\) parameters in total.

  • The kernel tensor can be denoted as \(K_i^{\frac{c}{v} \frac{d}{v}}\) where \(0 \le i \lt v\) is group index. It leads to alternative factorization of general convolution.

Convolution Variants are Factorizations

  • Depth-wise and grouped convolution are basically different ways to factorize kernels.

  • Using the same idea, let’s invent a channel-independent convolution.

\[K_{c}^{k d} = F_c^e K_{e}^{k d}\]

where \(F_c^e\) changes the input image from \(c\) to \(e\) channels. Then, apply the kernel \(K_{e}^{k d}\) with fixed number of in/output channels.

Composition of Convolution Kernel

Suppose two consecutive convolutions:

  • First, \(K_{c_1}^{k_1 c_2}\) goes from \(c_1\) to \(c_2\) channels with kernel size \(k_1\).

  • \(K_{c_2}^{k_2 c_3}\) goes from \(c_2\) to \(c_3\) channels with kernel size \(k_2\).

  • We can compose the two into one kernel.

\[K_{c_1}^{k_1 c_2} K_{c_2}^{k_2 c_3} = K_{c_1}^{\langle k_1 \cdot k_2 \rangle c_3}\]

Composition of Convolution Kernel

Remarks Convolution Kernel Composition

  • Addition of two kernels works similarly.

  • That’s why we seldom run two convolutions consecutively.

CSPNet

Overview

  • CSPNet: A New Backbone that can Enhance Learning Capability of CNN (link)

  • Authored by Chien-Yao Wang and Hong-Yuan Mark Liao et al, same authors of YOLOv4.

  • YOLOv4 adopts this technique. It reduces up to 19% computation power at the same top-1 accuracy.

Computing DenseNet (Naïve)

Computing DenseNet (Naïve)

  • Let \(D_{i,j}\) the weight from ith to jth layer.

  • To compute jtj layer output \(x_j\), we compute the summation \(x_j = w_{0,j} x_0 + \cdots + w_{j-1,j} x_{j-1}\).

Computing DenseNet

Computing DenseNet

  • To compute jtj layer output \(x_j\), concatenate all previous layers first and apply to a big weight.

\[x_j = w_j \cdot \left [ x_0, x_1, \cdots, x_{j-1} \right ]\]
